author: @existingismypurpose7102
text: So this kind of feels like 'Scotland Yard' in real life with is cool. If you didn't know Scotland Yard is a board game set in London,  where up to 8 players ( I believe) dubbed detectives hunt one player who is dubbed mr x. Mr x has unlimited travel capabilites within London whilst the detectives have limited resources for taxi bus and subway. Mr x's location is reviewed every 5 turns and when a detective runs out of movement options he is out. If the detectives land on the same spot as Mr x, whether they know it or not, detectives win. If all detectives rum out of movement options mr x wins. There are randomised starting locations and the detectives can see mr x's moves once he does them

author: @tristanmoller9498
text:
You can play a small version of this in cities with good public transportation. Played it in Munich with friends, the friends only had to update their location every 12 or 13 minutes or so. It worked out well because there are bus lines, that take you as far as subway lines, as well as tram lines, that have more stops but take you around the neighborhood and low speed rail, that can take you to outskirts. Also, all of that is connected through one app on your phone in Munich. 

A lot of fun! And as a newcomer (new student) in the city, you get to know where you‚Äôre going real fast.

It was really fun and really tiring but would do this type of thing again.

author: @yama123numbercauseytdemand4
text:
20:09 easiest challenge possible: If I remember correctly, Jaywalking isn't even a thing outside of the US. So cross any street anywhere that also has a traffic sign a few hundred meteres down the street. Check.

Edit: I looked it up, which took 2min at most, here is what I found: In Colorado (USA) it is illegal to cross a road/street as a pedestrian anywhere else then at intersections and/or crosswalks. (Which in my eyes is a rule against humans and for cars, which is inherently problematic, but that is beside the point.)
In France however, and thereby also in Calais, it is legal to cross any street anywhere you please unless it is directly in front of a moving vehicle. (which would be stupid anyways).
Therefor: Cross any street *not* at an intersection or crosswalk and check off the challenge.

author: @VoIcanoman
text:
Lol, I love how Dunkirk is out, but Lille is in. If Ben and Adam had just stayed in Lille, they would've caught him! And all because of a "curse."

Unless he takes a ferry to Dover. Which he could conceivably do, then take the Eurostar to Paris. I think this is less likely though, because if Ben and Adam see him on that ferry, they will know immediately what his plan is, and could just go to Paris to intercept. It's a logistics game at that point. The ferry is 90 minutes, and the fastest train to Paris another 120, so that's 3.5 hours, and he'll definitely have to do multiple challenges in Dover (the ferry will cost him 900 coins, but the high-speed train will be 3,000 coins, so even though he'd get 750 coins in Dover for completing the curse card, he'd have to add just over 1,300 coins in Dover to pay for a ticket to Paris).

You know...it would almost make more sense to take the ferry to Dover, then take a train to London. He could do a whole bunch of challenges in London and then, after accumulating a lot of coins, he could FLY somewhere, ideally somewhere that has a good rail pathway to Zermatt. The upshot is that there would be no point for Ben and Adam to go to London to catch him. It'd be pointless, because a) once they realize Sam is going to London, it would likely take them a few hours to get there after him, and b) once they got to London, Sam could pick any one of London's 3 major airports to disembark from...or he could even take the Eurostar BACK to France and psych them out. Better to stay still in France and wait for him to return to the continent.

text: I haven't watched the next episode on Nebula, so I might be totally wrong, but Ben and Adam are missing something that Europeans would figure out quickly: The long-distance public transport in France is incredibly Paris-centric. author: @mfogs1767
text:
My thoughts on strategy:

Head to Germany ASAP. Germany has public bike sharing (Call a Bike) across ~40 cities. It's unclear whether you can pick up a bike in one city and drop it off in another. If you can, great, that makes things easier‚Äîbut if not, simply bike out into the countryside and start racking up challenges in obscure locations (this part would work in any city that has public bike sharing, not just DE). Start by biking along a major train route for 45 min so it looks like you're on the train (choose a low speed one so your speed looks conceivable; they may sniff this out). Choose a stop as far away that has no bike share and you can get there before they do on the next public transit. Stay there until the next public transit from the starting point departs. Then take off in a direction that has no public transit with your bike. Start racking up challenges, bouncing from place to place that doesn't have easy public transit opportunities in a randomized manner. 

You'll get a TON of points this way. Then - they know you'll have to return to the same city to return your bike. But rather than choosing the main train station or something, find an alternate departure point (e.g. intra-city bus stop, smaller train station, etc.). Get there max 5 min before your departure, fly off into the sunset. Granted, you could still be caught, BUT you have so many more options incl flights for later on based on how many pts you racked up. 

I don't have access to the full rules, but this seems possible based on what's been stated so far (but who knows they're pretty good about rules so it may not be possible). You would obviously have to be a very strong biker as well (I've done ~50 miles on a citi bike and it was a nightmare lol).
